issue(id="XXXX" status="open")
  title Teach redteam.js to choose adversarial probes from an informed target profile
  user-story
    as-a redteam.js developer building a reusable adversarial auditor
    i-want the harness to fingerprint the target platform and boundary model before choosing attack probes
    so-that its findings reflect the real exposure of each system instead of irrelevant platform theater
  premise.
    The next red-team harness should act less like a static checklist and more
    like a burglar who case-studies the house before picking tools. A Windows
    credential-theft playbook does not tell us much about a Linux sandbox, and
    a generic Linux probe set still misses important differences between
    Docker, WSL, bare metal, macOS-hosted VMs, and nested in-guest sandboxes.

    The first implementation should therefore begin with a target profile step
    that records where attacker code lands, which operating systems and
    isolation layers are actually in play, what secret stores matter on that
    platform, and which privilege boundaries are supposed to hold. Probe
    selection should flow from that profile and the report should explain both
    why a probe family ran and why a different family was skipped.

    The first concrete target profile should be `scrubs`. Its basic layout is:
    a trusted Darwin host acting as the thin client, a disposable Lima VM on
    the `vz` backend, a NixOS guest as the main developer environment, and an
    additional in-guest clean-versus-dirty split for `mise`-managed tooling.
    Dirty package-manager and runtime workloads are launched through a scrubs
    wrapper into `bubblewrap`, with a synthetic home, the project tree bound
    in, `/tmp` writable, `mise` data and config mounted read-only, curated
    helper commands under `/bin` and `/usr/bin`, and ambient low-sensitivity
    facts such as `/proc`, `/sys`, `/etc/hosts`, `/etc/resolv.conf`, and
    `/etc/localtime`. The primary audit boundary is not "can malware break out
    of macOS immediately"; it is "can package-borne attacker code running in
    dirty space reach clean guest credentials, unrelated guest files, or a
    credible exfiltration path anyway".
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion redteam.js records a target profile before platform-specific probing, including host OS, guest or container layers, execution OS, package ecosystems, intended trust boundaries, relevant secret stores, and expected network posture.
    criterion Probe selection is target-aware: the harness enables, suppresses, and explains attack families based on the recorded profile instead of pretending every target is the same machine.
    criterion The initial profile set includes a first-class `scrubs` target that captures the Darwin host, Lima plus `vz`, NixOS guest userland, and the in-guest `bubblewrap` dirty-runtime boundary.
    criterion The `scrubs` profile drives realistic dirty-runtime probes against the assets that matter here, including guest-local `gh`, Codex, SSH, `.env`, `.npmrc`, unrelated home-directory files, helper-command abuse, environment leakage, `/proc` inspection, subprocess pivots, writable-path escape attempts, and outbound exfiltration attempts.
    criterion The harness report clearly separates confirmed access, failed access, skipped platform families, and cross-boundary hypotheses so developers do not overclaim safety from the wrong passing tests.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Implement the control flow as `fingerprint -> map assets -> choose probe
      families -> run probes -> explain why each family ran or was skipped`.
      If the target looks like Windows, that should unlock Windows-specific
      credential and persistence probes; if it looks like a Linux guest inside
      a macOS VM, that should instead prioritize Linux filesystem, process,
      credential, and sandbox-boundary probes.
    item(status="open").
      For the initial `scrubs` adapter, assume attacker code lands as the
      unprivileged guest user through npm, pnpm, Bun, Cargo, or adjacent
      `mise`-resolved tooling inside the dirty wrapper. The first job is to
      attack the guest clean-versus-dirty split honestly before spending much
      time on host-only probes that require a separate VM-escape story.
    item(status="open").
      Model the current scrubs dirty habitat as having a synthetic `HOME`, a
      fake dirty `git` identity with no credential helper, the project root
      mounted writable, `/tmp` writable, read-only `mise` data and config, a
      curated helper basket including utilities such as `git`, `find`, `env`,
      `grep`, `sed`, `tar`, `unzip`, and `mise`, plus read-only access to
      `/proc`, `/sys`, `/etc/hosts`, `/etc/resolv.conf`, and
      `/etc/localtime`. Those details should shape what the burglar tries.
    item(status="open").
      Prioritize realistic package-borne attacker behavior: inspect
      `process.env`; search for secret-shaped files and directories; read
      unrelated guest-home material; inspect running processes and `/proc` for
      leaked arguments or environment; abuse helper commands and subprocess
      spawning; test whether dirty `git` can still reach auth; and attempt
      labeled outbound exfiltration to a controlled endpoint.
    item(status="open").
      Keep the report honest about platform mismatch. A skipped Windows
      registry probe or macOS keychain probe should appear as "not applicable
      to this target profile", not as a passed security check for `scrubs`.
